6. haec sapit. She is the goddess of worldly wisdom and bankeress to all Olympus. The construction of fenerat with accusative of the person is apparently unique. But the emen- dation suggested, temperat and monetae for Minervae absolutely freezes the humour of the passage. Minerva discounting bills for all the gods is, as Roman wit goes, a humorous idea. The other would be tame in the extreme. The same remark will apply to the attempt to translate fenerat deos ‘lends you all the gods on usury' being too canny to give them for nothing. This is not merely tame, but unintelligible.

7. hederae, i.e. the Thyrsus. Bacchus was affiociated with Apollo, as the god who inspired poets, cf. Hor. Odes 111. xxv. 1. Quo me, Bacche, rapis tui Plenum? and JUV. vn. 64. dominis Cirrhae Nysaeque feruntur Pectora vestra.
